#TeaganAir
The flight log book has officially been put into use. I now have 2.3 hours of flight time recorded ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I were to describe what it feels like to fly a small aircraft, I would say it's like riding a motorcycle/ATV and boat combined, at 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, things change in an instant. There is a certain degree of instability on the ground, so a motorcycle/ATV is needed.
Additionally, you might not know that when driving a plane on the ground, you use your feet to control the direction, not the control stick. You use the rudder pedals and brakes. It's not like a car.
When flying in the air, you will feel turbulence and shaking, which feels like being on a ship sailing on water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the air currents can make you feel a bit dizzy, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like a sailor adapts to sailing.
There is also a random little tidbit about this:
Flying is very physically demanding. My back and legs are really sore today, feeling like I went to the gym.
This is not as simple as a Sunday drive in a car. In my view, as a beginner, it feels more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, happy Saturday. Welcome to 4,000 feet high altitude.
Tomorrow I will fly again, and we will practice stalls and slow flight.
Today's weather was unstable, but super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed dropped as low as 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still 65 miles per hour.
Today was sunny, and although the high altitude was a bit misty, the visibility was still great.
